 "executive_summary": "This study examined a conserved TCR frequently selected during HIV-1 immune responses to an epitope presented by HLA-B*5701, but notably absent when the same epitope is presented by HLA-B*5703\u2014two alleles differing by only two concealed polymorphisms. Structural and biophysical analyses revealed that despite the two HLA-B*57 subtypes displaying the HIV epitope in conformationally identical formats, their polymorphic differences alter peptide positioning during TCR engagement, mediated by shifts in water-molecule interactions and coordination. These subtle MHC micropolymorphisms translate into measurable differences in TCR-binding kinetics and cellular function, demonstrating how minimal sequence variation in MHC-I can gate repertoire selection and TCR usage. The findings underscore a molecular mechanism by which MHC micropolymorphisms influence T-cell responses to infection and have implications for understanding differential susceptibilities to viral clearance and disease outcomes across individuals with closely related HLA types.",
